---
import Layout from '../../components/Layout.astro';
import SectionIntro from '../../components/SectionIntro.astro';
import ContactCTA from '../../components/ContactCTA.astro';
import projects from '../../data/projects.json';

const featured = projects.slice(0, 5);
const montagePreview = [
  projects.find((project)=>project.slug==='vps-vine-pod-system'),
  projects.find((project)=>project.slug==='air-new-zealand-terminals'),
  projects.find((project)=>project.slug==='amex-americas-cup-village'),
  projects.find((project)=>project.slug==='bnz-anz-reimaging'),
  projects.find((project)=>project.slug==='five-litre-measuring-jug'),
  projects.find((project)=>project.slug==='hospital-labelling-system')
].filter(Boolean);
const pillars = [
  ['Problem', 'Identify the real friction: use, cost, safety, programme, legibility, manufacture or movement through a place.'],
  ['Response', 'Turn the brief into something buildable: an object, system, environment, rollout plan or working prototype.'],
  ['Outcome', 'Hold the practical result in view: clearer use, safer handling, better delivery, lower cost or reliable implementation.'],
  ['Painting link', 'The same habits now surface in the paintings: structure, edges, sequence, material intelligence and visual nerve.']
];
---
<Layout title="Project Management — JungDesign" description="David Jung’s JungDesign project-management and design-delivery practice: commercial projects, aviation environments, retail rollouts and disciplined delivery.">
  <SectionIntro eyebrow="Project Management / Proof" title="David Jung has spent decades making complex design and development projects real." intro="Before painting became the main daily practice, JungDesign was a working design and project-management practice: products, environments, systems, rollouts and commercial problem-solving."/>

  <section class="dev-manifesto">
    <div class="dev-manifesto-mark">JD</div>
    <div>
      <span class="eyebrow">Professional spine</span>
      <p>JungDesign’s commercial work is the evidence behind the paintings: clear composition, practical judgement, careful sequencing, a feel for materials and a habit of turning vague problems into usable form.</p>
      <p>This is not a document dump. Each project is treated as a compact case study: what the problem was, what David/JungDesign did, why it mattered, and what changed because the work was done.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="career-pillars" aria-label="JungDesign project-management capabilities">
    {pillars.map(([title,copy],index)=><article>
      <b>{String(index+1).padStart(2,'0')}</b>
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      <p>{copy}</p>
    </article>)}
  </section>

  <section class="project-index" id="commercial-projects">
    <div class="project-index-intro">
      <span class="eyebrow">Commercial projects</span>
      <h2>Proof of method, not nostalgia.</h2>
      <p>These projects show David working where design has consequences: live airports, retail rollouts, hospitality deadlines, budgets, safety systems and manufactured products. The point is not to compete with the paintings, but to show the discipline that made them possible.</p>
      <a class="montage-preview-card" href="/design/montage/" aria-label="View Product Development image montage">
        <span class="eyebrow">Image montage</span>
        <div class="montage-preview-grid" aria-hidden="true">
          {montagePreview.map((project)=><img src={project.slug==='vps-vine-pod-system'?'/images/project-sources/vine-pod-overlay.jpg':project.image} alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async"/>) }
        </div>
        <strong>View the visual wall →</strong>
      </a>
    </div>
    <div class="project-feature-grid">
      {featured.map((project)=><a class="project-tile feature" href={`/design/${project.slug}/`}>
        <figure class:list={["project-source-image", `project-${project.slug}`]}><img src={project.image} alt={project.imageAlt} loading="lazy" decoding="async"/><figcaption>{project.visual.label}</figcaption></figure>
        <span>{project.number} / {project.type}</span>
        <h3>{project.title}</h3>
        <p>{project.summary}</p>
        <dl class="proof-points">
          <div><dt>Problem</dt><dd>{project.problem}</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Outcome</dt><dd>{project.outcome}</dd></div>
        </dl>
        <i>Read case study →</i>
      </a>)}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="career-spine">
    <span class="eyebrow">How to read this archive</span>
    <h2>Design here means responsibility.</h2>
    <p>Not just styling. Not just management. The recurring JungDesign move is to take responsibility for the whole chain: the object, the setting, the people using it, the money available, the deadline approaching and the detail that must still be right.</p>
    <p>That is why this section belongs on a painting site. It explains the confidence of the work without over-explaining the paintings themselves.</p>
  </section>

  <blockquote>“The paintings don’t leave design behind. They make its instincts visible.”</blockquote>
  <ContactCTA title="A project conversation?" copy="David welcomes selected project-management and development enquiries alongside questions about the paintings."/>
</Layout>
